        "message": "LU-19473 lnet: nid_addr_is_set false negatives\n\nNumeric based NIDs can have address \"0\". This causes problems for\nnid_addr_is_set() which can only look for a non-zero address value.\nThis causes two bugs:\n - If a node has multiple NIDs on one net, one of the NIDs has a 0\n   address, then an attempt to delete the 0 address NID will cause\n   all NIDs on the network to be removed.\n - If the source NID specified for lnetctl ping has a 0 address then\n   this is not correctly passed down to the kernel (so the ping is\n   processed as though no souce NID were specified).\n\nTo solve the first issue we pass a new flag to lnet_dyn_del_ni() to\nindicate whether to allow deletion of the entire network in that\nfunction. This is only needed for backward compatability with the\nIOCTL interface. The netlink callers of this function always pass a\nNID whose address has been \"set\".\n\nTo solve the second issue we modify jt_ping() to pass a NULL argument\nto yaml_lnet_ping() when a source nid has not been specified by the\nuser.\n\nA comment is added to nid_addr_is_set() to document the limitation of\nthis function.\n\nFixes: 277b07e175 (\"LU-18540 lnet: Fix lnetctl ping timeout parsing\")\nFixes: 8f8f6e2f36 (\"LU-10003 lnet: use Netlink to support old and new NI APIs.\")\nTest-Parameters: trivial\nSigned-off-by: Chris Horn <chris.horn@hpe.com>\nChange-Id: Id9c9f8ff93f7cdb040c9c166af4cdfcb64b2b6e8\nReviewed-on: https://review.whamcloud.com/c/fs/lustre-release/+/61822\nReviewed-by: Serguei Smirnov <ssmirnov@whamcloud.com>\nReviewed-by: Cyril Bordage <cbordage@whamcloud.com>\nTested-by: jenkins <devops@whamcloud.com>\nReviewed-by: Oleg Drokin <green@whamcloud.com>\nTested-by: Maloo <maloo@whamcloud.com>\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
